			      <div type="translation" xml:lang="eng">
				        <p>Pious gift to the noble community of monks, that is six — 6 — columns, of Siddhattha, belonging to the …tīya family, together with his brother, with his wife — the distinguished Hadā — with his son, with his daughter, with his daughter-in-law from a (respectable) house, with his grandchildren.</p>
			      </div>
			      <div type="commentary">
				        <p>Similarity of script, occurrence of the rare term <foreign xml:lang="pra-Latn">sagharasuṇhā</foreign>, and (near)
					correspondence of names of more than one donor, make it
					tempting to assume the protagonists of this inscription are
					the same as those of EIAD <ref target="#EIAD0298">298</ref>.</p>
            <listApp>
	              <app loc="2"> 
                  <lem>ghara<unclear>ṇ</unclear>iya</lem>
                  <note>On the meaning of this term, commonly featuring in South Indian inscriptions to characterize wives of prominent donors, see <bibl>
                        <ptr target="eiad-bibl:Nakanishi2014"/>: <citedRange>16–7</citedRange>
                     </bibl>.</note>
               </app>
	              <app loc="4"> 
                  <lem>sagharasunhaka<unclear>sa</unclear>
                  </lem>
                  <note>On the meaning of the term <foreign xml:lang="pra-Latn">gharasunhā</foreign>, see <bibl>
                        <ptr target="eiad-bibl:Hinüber2017"/>: <citedRange>6–9</citedRange>
                     </bibl>.</note>
               </app>
